From: REMU project <noreply@example.com>
Subject: [PATCH] hw/intc/arm_gicv3_cpuif: seed CPU interface reset state after init

gicv3_init_cpuif() defines the ICC_*_EL1 coproc registers on each ARM
CPU via define_arm_cp_regs(). The ICC_PMR_EL1 ARMCPRegInfo entry carries
icc_reset() as its .resetfn, which seeds architecturally-required reset
values on the GICv3CPUState -- most notably:

    cs->icc_bpr[GICV3_G0]   = icc_min_bpr(cs);      // 7 - prebits
    cs->icc_bpr[GICV3_G1]   = icc_min_bpr(cs);
    cs->icc_bpr[GICV3_G1NS] = icc_min_bpr_ns(cs);   // icc_min_bpr + 1
    cs->icc_ctlr_el1[{S,NS}] = ...pribits-derived...
    cs->icc_ctlr_el3          = ...pribits-derived...
    cs->ich_vmcr_el2          = ...vprebits-derived...

all of which read cs->pribits / prebits / vpribits / vprebits -- values
that are set only *inside* gicv3_init_cpuif() itself, *after* the
define_arm_cp_regs() call. The resetfn therefore cannot run correctly
until after gicv3_init_cpuif() has finished setting up the CPU
interface.

In the common upstream case (machines that create CPUs and then a GIC
from within a single machine-init function, followed by QEMU's
end-of-init qemu_system_reset()), the CPU is cold-reset at least once
more after gicv3_init_cpuif() has completed, so icc_reset() eventually
fires with the proper pribits/prebits in place. That second reset,
however, is not guaranteed by anything gicv3_init_cpuif() itself does
-- it is a happy side-effect of the typical machine-boot flow. Any ARM
CPU that is realized (and cold-reset once) *before* its GIC is realized
and that does not subsequently get re-reset (e.g. a machine's bootstrap
CPU that runs straight into firmware, with no PSCI CPU_ON warm-boot and
no explicit post-init reset) will therefore see ICC_* registers stuck
at C-zero-init values.

The most visible failure is icc_gprio_mask() tripping its spec-mandated
assert(bpr > 0) for GICV3_G1NS on the very first Group-1 NS SPI that
reaches that CPU, because ICC_BPR1_EL1 was never written to its
architectural reset value (minimum 1; typically 3 for prebits == 5).
icc_bpr_write() clamps software writes to that minimum, so the only
way the register can be 0 at the point of IRQ delivery is if icc_reset
never ran.

Fix this inside gicv3_init_cpuif() itself: once pribits / prebits /
vpribits / vprebits and all CPRegs are in place, call icc_reset()
directly on the CPU's env. This makes the CPU interface self-seed its
own reset state without relying on an externally-triggered CPU reset.

icc_reset() does not read its ARMCPRegInfo argument, so passing NULL is
safe.

Signed-off-by: REMU project <noreply@example.com>
---
 hw/intc/arm_gicv3_cpuif.c | 22 ++++++++++++++++++++++
 1 file changed, 22 insertions(+)

diff --git a/hw/intc/arm_gicv3_cpuif.c b/hw/intc/arm_gicv3_cpuif.c
index ea1d1b3..6506df7 100644
--- a/hw/intc/arm_gicv3_cpuif.c
+++ b/hw/intc/arm_gicv3_cpuif.c
@@ -3174,5 +3174,27 @@ void gicv3_init_cpuif(GICv3State *s)
             assert(!arm_feature(&cpu->env, ARM_FEATURE_EL2));
             assert(!arm_feature(&cpu->env, ARM_FEATURE_EL3));
         }
+
+        /*
+         * Seed ICC/ICH CPU-interface reset state now that pribits /
+         * prebits / vpribits / vprebits / num_list_regs are final and
+         * every CPReg (including the ICC_PMR_EL1 entry that carries
+         * icc_reset as its .resetfn) has been registered on the CPU.
+         *
+         * The .resetfn machinery would handle this automatically IF the
+         * CPU was guaranteed to see a cold reset after gicv3_init_cpuif()
+         * returns. But that is a property of the surrounding boot flow,
+         * not of this function: a bootstrap CPU that was cold-reset at
+         * qdev_realize() time and never goes through PSCI CPU_ON would
+         * otherwise keep icc_bpr[G1NS] == 0 and trip icc_gprio_mask()'s
+         * assert(bpr > 0) on the first Group-1 NS SPI it ever takes.
+         *
+         * Calling icc_reset() directly here makes the CPU interface own
+         * its own reset-state seeding, so it is correct regardless of
+         * whether anyone resets the CPU again later.
+         *
+         * icc_reset() does not read its ARMCPRegInfo argument.
+         */
+        icc_reset(&cpu->env, NULL);
     }
 }
